/* COMPILER/BOOT/cg_svir.iii — Γ1: THE SVIR BACKEND of the PRODUCTION compiler.
 *
 * Consumes the production parse-AST (lex.iii + parse.iii, the SAME front-end
 * that feeds cg_r3's x86 backend) and emits an SVIR v1 module.  Two laws:
 *
 *   CANONICAL   — for the width-free fragment (i64/untyped scalars, u8 module
 *                 arrays: everything iiisv2 can express) the emission is
 *                 BYTE-IDENTICAL to iiisv2 (DOCS/SVIR-V1-CANONICAL.md).
 *   FAITHFUL    — for width-carrying programs (Θ2-full rung 2) the emission
 *                 implements THE DEFINITIONAL LAW (eval.iii, square-proven):
 *                 values live on the SVIR stack in eval's NORMAL FORM
 *                 (unsigned: zero-extended, signed: sign-extended to 64) and
 *                 every op renormalizes exactly where ev_binop/ev_adapt do —
 *                 masks after narrow add/sub/mul/shl, bias-XOR for u64/ptr-
 *                 free unsigned ordered compares, DIV_U/REM_U (0x2A/0x2B)
 *                 for unsigned division, &31 shift counts below 64 bits
 *                 (ev_shmask), logical `>>` for ALL int types (pinned p10).
 *
 * Everything outside the supported fragment is REFUSED LOUDLY with a named
 * class (`svir-unsup class=... kind=...` on stderr, nonzero return) — the
 * corpus sweep's S-frontier census.  NO SILENT MISCOMPILES.
 *
 * Independence: consumes AST only — NO sema, NO sid, NO cg_r*, NO emit/link.
 * (Types come from declarations + suffixes + eval's unify law, the same
 * derivation the definitional evaluator performs; sema stays out of route S.)
 */
module cg_svir

